    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Introduction to 'Job' and 'Work'",
          "arabic": "مقدمة عن 'وظيفة' و 'عمل'"
        },
        "text": "In Arabic, common words for 'job' or 'work' are 'وظيفة' (waẓīfah) which typically means 'job' or 'position', and 'عمل' (ʿamal) which can mean 'work' or 'deed'. 'مهنة' (mihnah) also refers to 'profession'. For this lesson, we will focus on 'وظيفة' and 'عمل'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "ما هي وظيفتكَ؟",
            "english": "What is your job? (masc.)",
            "transliteration": "Mā hiya waẓīfatuka?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ما هو عملُكَ؟",
            "english": "What is your work? (masc.)",
            "transliteration": "Mā huwa ʿamaluka?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'What is your job?'",
          "arabic": "كيف تسأل: 'ما وظيفتك؟'"
        },
        "text": "To ask someone about their job, you can use 'ما وظيفتكَ؟' (Mā waẓīfatuka?) for a male or 'ما وظيفتكِ؟' (Mā waẓīfatuki?) for a female. Another common way to ask 'What do you do?' or 'What do you work as?' is 'ماذا تعملُ؟' (Mādhā taʿmalu?) for a male and 'ماذا تعملينَ؟' (Mādhā taʿmalīna?) for a female.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "ما وظيفتكَ؟",
            "english": "What is your job? (to a male)",
            "transliteration": "Mā waẓīfatuka?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ما وظيفتكِ؟",
            "english": "What is your job? (to a female)",
            "transliteration": "Mā waẓīfatuki?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "ماذا تعملُ؟",
            "english": "What do you do? (to a male)",
            "transliteration": "Mādhā taʿmalu?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Answering 'I am a...'",
          "arabic": "الإجابة: 'أنا ...'"
        },
        "text": "When answering about your job, you say 'أنا' (anā) meaning 'I am', followed by your profession. Remember that many professions have masculine and feminine forms in Arabic. For example, 'أنا طالبٌ' (anā ṭālibun - I am a student, male) vs. 'أنا طالبةٌ' (anā ṭālibatun - I am a student, female).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أنا طالبٌ.",
            "english": "I am a student. (male)",
            "transliteration": "Anā ṭālibun."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أنا طالبةٌ.",
            "english": "I am a student. (female)",
            "transliteration": "Anā ṭālibatun."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أنا أعملُ في شركة.",
            "english": "I work in a company.",
            "transliteration": "Anā aʿmalu fī sharikah."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
